re is a samāʿ on Shehit Ali 2826 dated 22nd of Dhū al-Ḥijja 626H.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Probably Damascus </DATA></COL><COL><DATA>al-ḥamdu lillāh ḥamd al-ḥamd </DATA></COL><COL><DATA>A treatise on the servants of God according to the different character traits (akhlāq) of the perfect human being (al-insān al-kāmil). Each servant (ʿabd Allāh) represents a spiritual modality symbolised by the association of a Divine Name and the name of a particular prophet or saint. The work is in two parts; the first consisting of 50 ʿabādila divided into five sections, the second of 67. Pablo Beneito supports Michel Chodkiewicz in relating the first 114 to the 114 suras of the Qurʾān. </DATA></COL><COL><DATA>OY lists 16 mss., at least seven of which can be considered historic. The best is Yusuf Aga 4859, a partial holograph with a samāʿ dated 641H. Different copies have different numbers of chapters: Ayasofia 4817 and Yusuf Aga 4859 have 117, Shehit Ali  2826  114, the Cairo printed edition (1969) 96. According to Pablo Beneito, who has made a detailed study of the text, 117 is the correct number. </DATA></COL><COL><DATA>177</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>188</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>&lt;638</DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="83" RECORDID="339"><COL><DATA>9</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>339</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>K. al-Ajwiba al-ʿArabiyya fī sharḥ al-naṣāʾiḥ al-Yūsufiyya</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>كتاب الأجوبة العربية في شرح النصائح الوسفية</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Verified B</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>ajwiba</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>al-ḥamdu lillāh alladhī hadānā li-hadhā wa-mā kunā li-nahtadī lawlā an hadānā Allāh laqad jaʿat rusul rabbina bi-l-ḥaqq</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Wise sayings, accompanied by explanatory notes. IA says in the introduction that it is a collection of sayings by a certain mystic called ʿAlī al-Kurdī who was ‘smitten with divine love’, and he has appended a commentary on these sayings.  Claude Addas adds: “Al-Ajwiba al-‘Arabiyya fî sharh al-nasâ’ih al-Yûsufiyya est une commentaire par Ibn ‘Arabî d’une risâla concernant les devoirs du murîd à l’égard de son shaykh rédigée par  Yûsuf b. Ibrâhîm al-Shâfi’î sous l’inspiration de la rûhâniya de ‘Alî al-Kurdî, un “fou” (muwallah ) notoire de Damas (I.A. l’a rencontré, cf.,Fut., II, 522, ed. Bûlaq).”</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>OY lists five mss. of  which two, Husein Celebi 447 and Yusuf Aga 4860, although undated, are very early, whilst  Yusuf Aga 4860 is from SQ’s library, and is possibly 7th or 8th century. The internal evidence of the text – for example, the language and the mention of his wife – is strong evidence that it is by IA. In addition, the title is listed in one of the lists which IA made of his own works, Fihris muʾallafāt al-shaykh al-akbar (RG142), and it does not seem to be attributed to anyone else.  Claude Addas confirms this stating that:: “L’attribution de ce texte  à Ibn ‘Arabî ne fait aucun doute ; on y trouve de nombreuses références autobiographiques, par ex, l’investiture de la khirqa par ‘Abd Allâh b. Jâmī”.A number of the poems in this work appear clustered in the Paris Diwan (B.N. 2348) and seemingly nowhere else. Further information on the fully digitized text of RG 9 found in Word format at cb.rayaheen.net/userfiles/download.php?id=1395‎, which extracts as a Word document with name شرح روحانية الشيخ الكردي.doc. The text itself carries a title not listed by Osman Yahia under RG 9, namely: شرح ما نطقت به روحانية سيدي علي الكردي .JC has compared that text to Yusuf Aga 4860 and Husein Celebi 447. The 202 page text in the Word document closely matches the complete text found in Husein Celebi 447 ff.1a-149b. Decapitated Yusuf Aga 4860 p.207 – which we estimate is missing the first 14 pages (7 folios) – starts with the text found at the end of page 11 of the Word document (cf. Husein Celebi f.9a line 2).PDF versions are also available via Google (شرح روحانية الشيخ الكردي لسيدي ابن عربي.pdf).</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>191</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>&lt;700</DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="128" RECORDID="123"><COL><DATA>26</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>123</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>K. al-Alif wa-huwa kitāb al-aḥadiyya</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>كتاب الألف وهو كتاب الأحدية</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Verified A.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>alif</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>IA</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>601</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>‘I composed it in Jerusalem (Bayt al-Muqaddas) in an hour of the daytime.’” (Vel.51/19a)</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Jerusalem</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>aḥadiyya ḥamd al-wāhid fī al-waḥdāniyyatihi</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Treatise on the unity symbolically represented by the letter Alif. Alternative title is K. al-Aḥadiyya.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Over 30 mss. are listed by OY, of which six can be considered to be historic. The best is Shehit Ali 2813, which was copied by Ayyūb b. Badr and read in front of IA in Damascus in 621H. According to OY, the work was written in 601H in Jerusalem on the basis of a note on Veliyuddin 51, but our investigation shows that no date is given. (See Jane Clark and Denis McAuley, Some Notes on the Manuscript Veliyuddin 51, JMIAS, 40 (2006), pp. 101-116.)</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>74</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>79</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>621</DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="73" RECORDID="266"><COL><DATA>28</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>266</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>K. al-Amr al-muḥkam</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>كتاب الأمر المحكم</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Verified A.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>amr_muh</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>IA</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>602</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>In Damascus in Jumada al-ūla 602H (see Vel.51/110b)</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Damascus</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>al-ḥamdu lillāh alladhī hadānā li-hadhā wa-mā kunā li-nahtadī lawlā 