n  Islamic Sainthood in the Fullness of Time (Leiden, 1999) pp. 197-199), which was written in 597H, and is the oldest known  ms. of  IA’s. Also excellent is Private 1, written  in 637H by a well-known disciple, Muḥammad b. ʿAbd al-Qādir al-Anṣāri, in Damascus and checked against the original in IA’s hand; however, according to Abrar Ahmed Shahi, who has prepared a critical edition of the text, this mss contains only about 50% of the work.Another early copy, dated 707H in the Turkish catalogue (http://ktp.isam.org.tr/), is Veliyuddin 1743 ff.1-79. Another copy, dated 834H, in Milli Hk 15 ff.12b-43b, is available in digital reproduction here: https://www.yazmalar.gov.tr/detay_goster.php?k=77129JC notes that most of the poems from ʿAnqāʾ mughrib are also found as a block – and as complete poems – in the Dīwān, p. 26-33. </DATA></COL><COL><DATA>61</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>65</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>597</DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="128" RECORDID="103"><COL><DATA>33</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>103</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>R. al-Anwār (K. Asrār al-khalwa)</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>رسالة الأنوار (كتاب أسرار الخلوة)</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Verified A.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>anwar</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>602</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Konya</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>al-ḥamdu li wāhib al-ʿaql wa-mubdiʿhi</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Written in answer to a request from a friend and companion that he should explain the journey of ascension to the ‘lord of power’ and the return to the creatures.  It describes the spiritual quest in terms of a non-stop ascension through the various levels of existence and knowledge leading to the level of human perfection. </DATA></COL><COL><DATA>A very commonly copied work in the early collections, verified by at least four historic mss. The best is probably Yusuf Aga 7838, which is from the SQ’s library, with a samāʿ dated 651H in Aleppo in SQ’s hand.