mad, each associated with a knowledge; for example; the wisdom on divinity in the word of Adam: the wisdom of light in the word of Joseph. Ibn ʿArabī’s intention in the Fuṣūṣ  is to draw out the interior, saintly wisdom of each prophet rather than the religious law which they brought.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>A much copied and commented on work, verified by at least seven historic mss. The best is Evkaf Muzesi 1933, which is SQ’s riwāya. written in his hand in 630H, with two samāʿ  in IA’s hand. Other early mss: Kastamonu Hk 2024 (710H), Paris 1340 (726H), Corum Hk 3909 (728H), Konya Ak 308 (757H) </DATA></COL><COL><DATA>187</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>194</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>630</DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="185" RECORDID="11"><COL><DATA>135</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>11</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>al-Futūḥāt al-Makkiyya</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>الفتوحات المكية</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Verified A</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>fut_mak</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>IA</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>629/636</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Damascus</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>al-ḥamdu lilāh alladhī awjad al-ashiyāʾ ʿan ʿadam wa-ʿadamahu wa-awqaf wajūdahā ʿalā tuwajjah kalimihi li-nataḥaqqaq bidhālik sir ḥudūthhā wa-qidamahā min qidamahi</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Ibn ʿArabī’s great summary of esoteric knowledge, consisting of 560 chapters and extending to nearly 10,000 pages in the holograph. It totalises all aspects of his work and all the esoteric knowledge of his era. The first recension, completed in Ṣafar 629H, exists only in copies, while the second, written between 632H and 636H, survives in IA’s own hand (see Evkaf Muzesi 1845+).There is still work to be done in distinguishing between the two recensions in the mss base, but considerable progress has been made by Julian Cook and Claude Addas in identifying “markers” which indicate the recension of any given ms. Their research indicates that many later mss. may be hybrids of the two recensions. For details of their work on the two recensions, see ancillary documents. </DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Verified by many mss. in both recensions. The best of the second recension is Evkaf Muzesi 1845+ in 37 volumes, which is the original in IA’s hand, written in 636H and carrying  over 71 samāʿ. </DATA></COL><COL><DATA>50</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>50</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>636</DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="48" RECORDID="16"><COL><DATA>219</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>16</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>K. al-Ḥaqq</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>كتاب الحق</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Verified A.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>haqq</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>IA</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>al-hamdu li-l-dhāt al-wāḥida min jamīʿ al-wujūh </DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Treatise on the real being.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>OY cites 35 mss. of which at least five can be considered historic. The best are Shehit Ali 2813 which was written by Ayyūb b. Badr in 621H in Damascus, and read in front of IA, and Private 1, copied during IA’s lifetime. </DATA></COL><COL><DATA>119</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>129</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>621</DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="105" RECORDID="19"><COL><DATA>237</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>19</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Ḥilyat al-abdāl</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>حلية الأبدال</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Verified A.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>hil_abd</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>599</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Holograph copy 7th Rabiʿ al-awwal 602H in Malatya (Yusuf Ağa 4868)</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Ṭāʾif</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>al-ḥamdu lillāh ʿalā mā alḥama wa-in ʿallamanā mā lam nakun naʿlam</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Treatise on the four essentials of the Way – silence, seclusion, hunger and wakefulness – as the means to the attainment of the spiritual station of the  Substitutes (al-abdāl). </